- Introduced in Java 8, this pool uses the fork-join framework and is based on a work-stealing algorithm
- Each processor core has its own queue. If one core finishes its tasks and becomes idle,
  it "steals" tasks from the queues of other busy cores to maximize CPU utilization
- By default, it maintains a number of threads equal to the number of processor cores available in the system.

submit() vs execute():

- execute(Runnable) — fire and forget, returns void
- submit(Runnable) — returns a Future<?>, lets you check for exceptions or cancellation later

The Future is discarded here, but submit is still preferred because unchecked exceptions inside execute()
can silently kill the worker thread, whereas submit() wraps them in the Future.